   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Much Ado
                           About Nothing</title></hi>]. <note>"Remarks." <hi rendition="#italics"
                                 ><title><title>Much Ado About Nothing</title>; A Comedy, In Five
                              Acts; By <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William
                                 Shakspeare</ref>. As Performed at the Theatres Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref> and <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>. Printed
                              Under the Authority of the Managers From the Prompt Book. With Remarks
                              by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                           Inchbald</ref></title></hi>, London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees,
                        and Orme, Paternoster Row, pp. 3-5. <hi rendition="#italics"><title
                              level="m">The British Theatre; or, A Collection of Plays, Which Are
                              Acted At the Theatres Royal, <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury
                                 Lane</ref>, <ref target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent
                                 Garden</ref>, and <ref target="people.html#Haymarket"
                                 >Haymarket</ref>. Printed Under the Authority of the Managers from
                              the Prompt Books. With Biographical and Critical Remarks, by <ref
                                 target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs. Inchbald.</ref></title></hi>
                        In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. II. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#HenryIVKingofEngland">King Henry IV</ref>.
                              First Part</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#HenryIVKingofEngland">King Henry IV</ref>.
                              Second Part</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Merchant of
                              Venice</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#HenryVKingofEngland">King Henry
                           V</ref></title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Much Ado About
                              Nothing</title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and
                        Orme, Paternoster Row. 1808. The first performance of this play was staged
                        in 1598 or 1599. Laura DeWitt and Mary A. Waters edited this essay for <hi
                           rendition="#italics">The Criticism Archive</hi>. </note>
                     <lb rendition="#center"/>______ </title>
               </bibl>
            </head>
            <p>The story of this comedy is supposed, by <ref target="people.html#PopeAlexander"
                  >Pope</ref>, to have been taken from the fifth book of <ref
                  target="people.html#Ariosto">Ariosto</ref>'s <title>Orlando
                  Furioso</title>.<note>Stated in <ref target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel"
                     >Johnson</ref> and <ref target="people.html#SteevensGeorge">Steevens</ref>' <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>The Plays of <ref
                           target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William Shakspeare</ref>. With
                        the Corrections and Illustrations of Various Commentators</title></hi>
                  (1773), vol. 2, p. 224. <ref target="people.html#Ariosto">Lodovico Ariosto</ref>'s
                     <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Orlando Furioso</title></hi> is a chivalric
                  romance epic which may have influenced <ref
                     target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakespeare</ref> through a possible
                  character archetype for Benedick.</note></p>
            <p><ref target="people.html#SteevensGeorge">Steevens</ref> says, there is as remote an
               original to be traced in <ref target="people.html#SpenserEdmund">Spenser</ref>'s
                  "<title>Fairy Queen</title>."<note>Stated in <ref
                     target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Johnson</ref> and <ref
                     target="people.html#SteevensGeorge">Steevens</ref>' <hi rendition="#italics"
                        ><title>The Plays of <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William
                           Shakspeare</ref>. With the Corrections and Illustrations of Various
                        Commentators</title></hi> (1773), vol. 2, p. 224. <ref
                     target="people.html#SpenserEdmund">Spenser</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"
                        ><title>The Faerie Queene</title></hi> contains a plot similar to that of
                  Claudio and Hero in <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Much Ado About
                     Nothing</title></hi>.</note></p>

            <p>"<title>Much ado about Nothing</title>" has more charms in its dialogue, than in its
               fable, or events. The first plot appears a trivial one, because all the incidents of
               note, which arise from it, are connected with persons of so little consequence in the
               piece, that their vicissitudes of fortune excite not that hope, fear, nor curiosity
               in the audience, which more important characters would inspire.</p>

            <p>Claudio and Hero<note>Count of Florence and daughter of Leonato, governor of Messina,
                  respectively. One of the play's two plots hinges on Claudio falling in love with
                  Hero, then being deceived that she is unfaithful. After publicly denouncing her,
                  he learns the truth, regrets his harsh actions, and eventually they reconcile and
                  marry.</note> are said to be in love, but they say so little about it themselves,
               that no strong sympathy is created, either by their joys, or their sorrows, their
               expectations or disappointments;&#8212;though, such is the reverence for justice
               implanted in humankind, that every spectator feels a degree of delight in the final
               vindication of her innocence, and the confusion of her guilty accusers.</p>

            <p>Those persons, for whom the hearts of the audience <fw type="sig"><hi
                     rendition="#smcaps">b 2</hi></fw><pb n="4"/>are most engaged, have, on the
               contrary, scarce one event to aid their personal interest: every occurrence, which
               befalls them, depends solely on the pitiful act of private listening. If Benedick or
                  Beatrice<note>Benedick is a lord and soldier from Padua, and Beatrice is the niece
                  of Leonato.</note> had possessed perfectly good manners, or just notions of honour
               and delicacy, so as to have refused to have become eves-droppers, the action of the
               play must have stood still, or some better method have been contrived&#8212;a worse
               hardly could&#8212;to have imposed on their mutual credulity.</p>

            <p>But this willingness to overhear conversations, the reader will find to be the
               reigning fashion with the dramatis personæ of this play; for there are nearly as many
               unwarrantable listeners, as there are characters in it.</p>

            <p>But, in whatever failings the ill-bred custom of Messina may have involved the said
               Benedick and Beatrice, they are both highly entertaining, and most respectable
               personages. They are so witty, so jocund, so free from care, and yet so sensible of
               care in others, that the best possible reward is conferred on their
               merit&#8212;marriage with each other.</p>

            <p>What <ref target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Dr. Johnson</ref> has said in respect to
               authors writing characters for provincial, or foreign pronunciation, may be applied
               to those, who produce such parts as Dogberry,<note>As the constable charged with
                  Messina's night watch, the ridiculous and incompetent Dogberry has an
                  over-inflated perception of his importance to the town.</note> that please merely
               by misapplication of words&#8212;"This mode of forming ridiculous characters, can
               confer praise only on him who originally discovered it, for it requires not much
               either of wit, or judgment. Its success must be derived almost wholly from the
               player; but its power in a skilful mouth, even he who despises it, is unable to
                  resist."<note>From <ref target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Johnson</ref> and <ref
                     target="people.html#SteevensGeorge">Steevens</ref>' <hi rendition="#italics"
                        ><title>The Plays of <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William
                           Shakspeare</ref>. With the Corrections and Illustrations of Various
                        Commentators</title></hi> (1773), vol. 1, p. 312.</note></p>

            <pb n="5"/>
            <p><ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakspeare</ref> has given such an
               odious character of the bastard, John,<note>Don John, the illegitimate brother of Don
                  Pedro, Prince of Aragon.</note> in this play, and of the bastard, Edmund, in <ref
                  target="people.html#LearKingofBritain">King Lear</ref>, that, had those dramas
               been written in the time of <ref target="people.html#CharlesIIKingofEngland">Charles
                  the Second</ref>, the author must have been suspected of disaffection to half the
                  court.<note>The court of <ref target="people.html#CharlesIIKingofEngland">King
                     Charles II</ref> was notorious for its moral laxity. <ref
                     target="people.html#CharlesIIKingofEngland">Charles</ref> acknowledged at least
                  12 illegitimate children with several mistresses.</note></p>
         </div>
      </body>
